<H5>  6. Foreign Economic Exchange </H5>
  In 1993, Anhui's scope of opening to the outside world 
further expanded, and a comprehensive pattern of foreign 
economic exchanges and foreign trade initially took shape. As a 
result, economic exchanges with foreign countries were 
unprecedentedly active. Statistics show that in 1993, the value 
of exports reached $964 million, up 16 percent over 1992, and 
the value of imports hit $324 million, an increase of 18 
percent. The structure of exports was further improved. The 
share of manufactured goods among exports rose from 67.9 percent 
in 1992 to 72.2 percent. Propelled by the torrent of a market 
economy, exports by foreign-funded enterprises continued to grow 
by a large margin, with the value of their exports amounting to 
$96 million, up 91.1 percent over 1992, and their share of 
Anhui's total export value rose from 6.1 percent in 1992 to 10 
percent. 
  High growth was achieved in the utilization of foreign 
capital. In 1993, the province actually utilized $370 million of 
foreign capital, up 1.6 times. Of this total, $260 million was 
in the form of contracted direct foreign investment, up 4.2 
times. The number of foreign-funded enterprises rose by a large 
margin. In 1993, a total of 1,040 new foreign-funded 
enterprises were approved, the largest number approved since the 
introduction of reform and opening to the outside world. 
  Tourism continued to grow. In 1993, Anhui received 153,000 
foreigners who came to the province for sightseeing, visits, or 
other activities, 1.2 percent more than the previous year. 
Foreign exchange income from tourism amounted to $17.798 
million, up 25.5 percent. Construction projects and labor 
service projects contracted by Anhui Province with foreign 
countries in 1993 totaled $6.07 million, and the accomplished 
operations revenue reached $3.91 million. 
<H5>  7. Finance and Insurance Industry </H5>
  In 1993, Anhui's financial institutions earnestly 
implemented 
central guidelines for strengthening and improving macroeconomic 
regulation and control to rectify the financial order; halted 
illegal fund transfers; readjusted credit structure; as well as 
ensured funds needed for key constructions, industrial and 
agricultural production, and purchases of agricultural and 
sideline products. In addition, the institutions alleviated the 
shortage of circulatory funds in some key enterprises, 
effectively bringing about sustained, rapid, and healthy 
development for Anhui's national economy. 
  As of the end of 1993, Anhui's banks' various deposits 
totalled 49.439 billion yuan, up 10.08 billion yuan over that of 
the previous year. Of this, urban residents' savings deposits 
amounted to 25.237 billion yuan, up 6.296 billion yuan over that 
of the previous year; and rural residents' savings deposits 
totalled 8.944 billion yuan, up 2.222 billion yuan. The balance 
of various bank loans totalled 71.206 billion yuan, an increase 
of 12.667 billion yuan. Of this, the balance of circulatory 
fund loans totalled 50.681 billion yuan, up 8.119 billion yuan 
over that of the previous year; and fixed asset loans totalled 
14.259 billion yuan, up 3.418 billion yuan. The people's finance 
and investment sense was further enhanced as the purchase of 
shares, bonds, and various valued securities notably increased. 
  Insurance business enjoyed fairly rapid development. In 
1993, the total volume of various domestic property insurance 
Anhui underwrote totalled 108.93 billion yuan. In Anhui, over 
18,000 enterprise units bought property insurance, 6.7 million 
urban and rural households participated in family property 
insurance, and 11.183 million people were covered with various 
kinds of personal insurance. The total premium income of 
domestic and foreign insurance business as well as the 
endowment-type insurance reached 1.51 billion yuan, up 18.4 
percent over that of the previous year. The amount overfulfilled 
the income target. Income in domestic insurance business topped 
1.47 billion yuan, up 18.3 percent. Incomes in property 
insurance, various kinds of personal insurance, and 
foreign-related business all grew by fairly wide margins. 
Domestic and foreign insurance compensations and payments 
totalled 890 million yuan for the whole year, thereby 
contributing to healthy national economic development and social 
stability. 
<H5>  8. Science, Education, Culture, Public Health, and Sports </H5>
  In 1993, Anhui's scientific and technological undertakings 
thrived and played an active role in promoting high economic 
growth rate and upgrading the quality of operations. In the 
year, Anhui's 298 scientific and technological achievements won 
awards at provincial and ministerial levels and four projects 
won state awards, one of which was a state invention prize and 
three of which were state spark prizes. The patent business 
enjoyed further development. In 1993, the province received 
1,041 patent applications, up 11 percent over that of the 
previous year. Total accumulated patent rights authorized in 
the province numbered 4,555. In the year, major scientific and 
technological achievements in the province included study in 
factors of early pregnancy; diagnosis of Anhui's soil nutrition; 
and study in equilibrium in fertilization. 
  New progress was made in various educational undertakings. 
In 1993, Anhui enrolled 784 new graduate students, up 137 over 
that of the previous year. The number of graduate students 
totalled 1,949, an increase of 164. Institutes of higher 
learning in general studies enrolled 32,300 students for general 
and special courses, an increase of 35.6 percent; and the number 
of school students totalled 81,000, up 15,000 people. Secondary 
vocational and technical education continued to develop. There 
were 389,000 students (including 79,000 technical school 
students) studying in various types of secondary vocational 
schools; and 248,000 secondary and high school students studying 
in general secondary schools. The coverage of compulsory 
education program steadily developed. There were 2.0624 million 
students in junior secondary schools and 6.011 million pupils in 
primary schools in Anhui. The enrollment rate of school-age 
children between 7 and 11 was 98.3 percent; and 77.3 percent of 
primary school graduates continued their study in secondary 
schools, 5.0 percent higher than the previous year. The rates 
of drop-outs for junior secondary school and primary school 
students were 6.6 percent and 1.7 percent, respectively. 
  Adult education at various levels continued to develop and 
training classes in various job skills were conducted. In 1993, 
institutions of adult higher education had an enrollment of 
50,000 students, with 24,000 new students enrolled for general 
and special courses. In the entire year, 20,000 students 
graduated from adult secondary schools; 935,000 students studied 
in adult secondary and primary schools; 863,000 students 
underwent training in adult technical training schools; and 
677,000 illiterate people became literate. 
  Cultural undertakings prospered with each passing day. By 
the end of 1993, the province had 2,981 film projection units, 
94 artistic groups, 102 cultural centers, 83 public libraries, 
26 museums, and 3,959,000 volumes of reference materials in 
archives, covering an area of 121,000 square meters. It also 
had 56 radio stations, 80 radio transmitters and relay stations, 
32 television stations, 27,058,000 copies of magazines and 
242,440,000 copies of books. 
  Public health undertakings continued to grow. By the end of 
1993, there were 105,000 beds, up 2.6 percent over the previous 
year. There were 145,000 full-time health and technological 
workers, up 1.7 percent; of these, 62,000 were doctors, up 3.9 
percent, and 34,100 were technicians and nurses, up 1.4 percent. 
  New achievements were made in sports. In 1993, Anhui's 
athletes won 36 gold medals and 53.5 silver and bronze medals at 
major world and domestic competitions. There were 24 top-grade 
athletes and 162 top-grade referees. 
  Progress was made in topography. Some 3,155,000 yuan worth 
of topographic works was produced during the year, including 687 
maps drawn from field operations under controlled circumstances 
[wai ye kong zhi 1120 2814 2235 0455], 288.7 maps drawn from 
field operations under coordinated circumstances [wai ye tiao 
hui 1120 2814 6148 4940], 875 maps drawn from field surveys [wai 
ye ce tu 1120 2814 3261 0956], 490.7 maps drawn from infield 
operations, and 27 annotated maps [di tu bian zhi 0966 0956 4882 
0455]. These maps provided strong topographic support to 
various endeavors of economic construction. 
<H5>  9. Population and People's Livelihood </H5>
  Population growth was controlled to some extent. According 
to a sampling survey, Anhui's population birth rate stood at 
17.18 per thousand, down 1.58 per thousand from the previous 
year; the death rate stood at 6.51 per thousand, up 0.37 per 
thousand; and the natural growth rate stood at 10.67 per 
thousand, down 1.95 per thousand. Calculated by the percentage 
mentioned above, the total resident population at year-end stood 
at 58,970,000. 
  The income of urban and rural residents increased by a large 
margin. Data from sample surveys showed that the per capita 
income of urban residents for living expenses in 1993 was 
2,025.7 yuan, up 24.8 percent over the previous year, or a real 
growth of 9.1 percent if increases in commodity prices were 
excluded. The per capita net income of rural residents was 
724.5 yuan, an increase of 151 yuan or 26.3 percent, the largest 
increase since the beginning of reform and opening up. The real 
growth was 9.4 percent -- also a fairly large increase in the 
last decade and more -- if fluctuations in prices were excluded. 
  New progress was made in various labor reforms, and a labor 
service and employment system had taken shape gradually. In 
1993, the number of employment agencies at all levels in the 
province reached 504; some 146,000 people in urban and rural 
areas were provided jobs. The urban unemployment rate at the 
end of the year was 2.8 percent. Fairly rapid progress was made 
in the use of labor contract system. Contract workers in 
state-owned units reached 486,000, accounting for 9.6 percent of 
the total number of urban workers. Society took an increasingly 
larger role in insurance for the aged. Some 1.834 million 
workers and 356,000 retirees were covered by social insurance, 
which has been expanded to entire society. The number of 
workers at the end of 1993 stood at 5,077,000, 510,000 of whom 
were urban private enterprise employees and self-employed 
workers. 
  The wage levels of workers rose further in 1993. Aggregate 
payroll for the year reached 13.65 billion yuan, up 21.7 percent 
over 1992; per capita wages reached 2,650 yuan, an increase of 
385 yuan or 17 percent -- an increase of 2.3 percent in real 
terms if price factors were excluded. 
  Housing conditions in both urban and rural areas continued 
to 
improve. In 1993, new housing units with a total area of 
46,400,000 square meters were built in urban and rural areas. 
Of the total, 8,010,000 square meters were built in urban 
areas, while 38,390,000 square meters were built in rural areas. 
  Social welfare undertakings continued to develop. In 1993, 
there were 52,000 beds in all sorts of social welfare facilities 
across the province, accommodating 44,000 people. A total of 
1,187,000 people in both urban and rural areas were served by 
various forms of social welfare. A rural social security 
network was established in 17.2 percent of the townships and 
towns in the province. Major progress was also made in the 
urban social service network. A total of 2,531 community 
service facilities and 5,395 service points were established. 
  Environmental protection undertakings developed at a faster 
pace. At the end of 1993, there were 2,234 workers at various 
environmental protection departments. There were 88 environment 
monitoring stations and 10 nature preserves in various parts of 
the province. A total of 122 environmental pollution control 
projects with an investment of 58,920,000 yuan were completed 
within the prescribed time in 1993. By the end of the year, 72 
smoke and dust control zones covering an area of 2,698,000 
square kilometers were established in 16 cities, and 49 noise 
pollution controlled zones covering an area of 79.8 kilometers 
were established in 11 cities. 
Footnotes: 
  1. Gross domestic product and added values of various 
industries quoted in the communique are based on the prices of 
the same year, whereas growth rates are based on comparable 
prices. 
  2. Base year figures for comparing various norms are from 
official statistics published in the previous year's Anhui 
Statistics Yearbook. 
  3. Added values are newly created values, mainly workers' 
remunerations, profits, tax revenues, and depreciation; 
excluding values of intermediate consumption, such as energy and 
raw and semifinished materials. 

